Reset apparel status to `clean` if previously `worn`.
Simulating an event in the real world where send your clothes to wash.
==== Current implementation - Wash a single indicated apparel
The wash command takes in only one parameter:
* Index: Index number of an apparel in filtered/unfiltered list. Only positive numbers present in list are valid.
When the user inputs the wash command in the CLI, the input is parsed, and the index of the apparel specified are tokenized and extracted.
`wash` keyword will call a constructor for WashCommandParser to parse the `index`, 1, creating a WashCommand for LogicManager.
LogicManager executes WashCommand which calls Model to set the apparel in the list to `clean`, and commits the changes to Storage.
The CommandResult object that is returned by the wash command lets the user know that the status of the apparel has been reset to `clean` or that it is already `clean`.
* Alternate command word: `available 1` works the same and is identical to `wash 1`
Pros: Gives the user a choice and a more intuitive approach to wardrobe management
* Input: Not allowing user to wash an already-clean Apparel again.
Pros: Reminds the user that his apparel is already clean if user absentminded types command.
Pros: Saves CPU time as it is not commiting to Addressbook. Throws exception instead.
A washAll command to simulate throwing all your dirty clothes into the washing machine.
Sets apparel status to `worn` whether its previous status was `clean` or `worn` and increases usage count by one.
Simulating an event in the real world where throw your worn clothes to the laundry basket
==== Current implementation - Wear a single indicated apparel
The wear command takes in only one parameter:
* Index: Index number of an apparel in filtered/unfiltered list. Only positive numbers present in list are valid.
When the user inputs the wash command in the CLI, the input is parsed, and the index of the apparel specified are tokenized and extracted.
`wear` keyword will call a constructor for WearCommandParser to parse the `index`, 1, creating a WearCommand for LogicManager.
LogicManager executes WashCommand which calls Model to set the apparel in the list to `worn`, and commits the changes to the Apparel to Storage.

The CommandResult object that is returned by the wear command lets the user know that the status of the apparel has been set to `worn` and returns and random message if the indicated apparel was already `worn` before command was executed.
* Alternate command word: `unavailable 1` works the same and is identical to `wash 1`
Pros: Gives the user a choice and a more intuitive approach to wardrobe management
* Input: Allowing user to wear an already-clean Apparel again.
Pros: Simulates the real world where people might not have time to wash their clothes due to bad time management and instead throws on the next thing in the wardrobe.
A wear command that takes in multiple INDEXs to simulate wearing a whole outfit out. e.g. `wear 1 2 3` to wear Apparel no. 1, 2 and 3.
Sort the list of items based on the options given. The sorting will be increasing order of the name of the option specified.

Simulating an event in the real world where users arrange their wardrobe according to the category of their choice. For example, in a wardrobe where the folded shirts and pants are stacked on top of one another, the user might want to put all the shirts on top of all the pants.
The sort command takes in one parameter. The valid arguments are: NAME, COLOR, and TYPE.
* Name  : The full name of the apparel.
* Color : The color of the apparel.
* Type  : The clothing type of the apparel.

e.g `sort color` will sort the apparels by color. If there are only 3 colors - Red, Black, Blue - in the wardrobe, calling `sort color` will arrange all the apparels in the following color starting from top - Black, Blue, Red.
When the user inputs the sort command in the CLI, the input is parsed, and the sorting option specified are validated.
`sort` keyword will call a constructor for SortCommandParser to parse the sort option, *color*, creating a SortCommand for LogicManager.
LogicManager executes SortCommand which calls Model to sort the apparels in the list by color, and commits the changes to Storage.
Simulating an event in the real world where users swap the position of two apparels.
The sort command takes in two parameters: INDEX_A and INDEX_B
* Index_A  : The first apparel to be swapped.
* Index_B : The second apparel to be swapped.
e.g `swap 2 5` will swap the apparels at index 2 and 5.

* *Alternative 1 (current choice):* Go through all the apparels in Fashion Match and displays statistics whenever the statistics command is called.
** Pros: This approach is less intensive on the computational power of the user's PC, as the command is only executed whenever the user calls it.
** Cons: Less user friendly as statistics will not be real-time
* *Alternate 2:* Updates statistics in real-time and whenever the statistics command is used.
** Pros: This approach is more user-friendly as users would not need to type `stats` command after new apparel is changed.
** Cons: Time-consuming and not scalable. This method could be more computationally more intensive, especially if the user has a large wardrobe.

Fashion Match (FM) is for those who *prefer to use a desktop app for managing dresswear*. More importantly, FM is *optimized for those who prefer to work with a Command Line Interface* (CLI). If you can type fast, AB4 can get your contact management tasks done faster than traditional GUI apps. Interested? Jump to the <<Quick Start>> to get started. Enjoy!
.  Ensure you have Java version `9` or later installed in your Computer.
.  Copy the file to the folder you want to use as the home folder for FM.
.  Double-click the jar file to start FM. The GUI will appear shortly after.
.  Type the command in the command box and press kbd:[Enter] to execute it. +
e.g. typing *`help`* and pressing kbd:[Enter] will open the help window.
.  Some example commands you can try:
* **`add`**`n/Cool Tshirt c/Green t/Top` : adds an apparel named `Cool Tshirt` to Fashion Match.
* **`delete`**`3` : deletes the 3rd apparel shown in the current list
.  Refer to <<Features>> for details of each command.
* Words in `UPPER_CASE` are the parameters to be supplied by the user e.g. in `add n/NAME`, `NAME` is a parameter which can be used as `add n/Formal Shirt`.
